{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584358"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:44:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:44:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14452"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14452"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0,0.09,0.14,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7147"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55479"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7147"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14452"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41019"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4906"},{"type":"tags","id":"4907"},{"type":"tags","id":"4910"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17063"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17159"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55479"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most characteristic histological feature occurring in the heart in acute rheumatic fever?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aschoff bodies","Caseating granulomas","Amyloid deposits","Myxomatous changes","Hyaline arteriolosclerosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most characteristic histological feature occurring in the heart in acute rheumatic fever is the presence of \u003Cstrong\u003EAschoff bodies\u003C/strong\u003E. These are focal lesions typically found in the myocardium and consist of areas of fibrinoid necrosis surrounded by T lymphocytes, macrophages, and occasional multinucleated giant cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaseating granulomas\u003C/strong\u003E are typically associated with tuberculosis and are not characteristic of acute rheumatic fever. \u003Cstrong\u003EAmyloid deposits\u003C/strong\u003E are seen in various systemic amyloidoses but are not a feature of acute rheumatic fever. \u003Cstrong\u003EMyxomatous changes\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with mitral valve prolapse and are not specific to acute rheumatic fever. \u003Cstrong\u003EHyaline arteriolosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a vascular change seen in hypertension and diabetes mellitus, not in acute rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile giant cells may be present in Aschoff bodies, they are not the defining feature. The presence of Aschoff bodies as a whole is more specific and characteristic of acute rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aschoff bodies are characteristic histological features of acute rheumatic fever in the heart.","Aschoff bodies consist of fibrinoid necrosis surrounded by T lymphocytes, macrophages, and occasional multinucleated giant cells."],"references":["Tandon, R., Sharma, M., Chandrashekhar, Y. et al. Revisiting the pathogenesis of rheumatic fever and carditis. Nat Rev Cardiol 10, 171\u2013177. 2013. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1038/nrcardio.2012.197","Carapetis, J., Beaton, A., Cunningham, M. et al. Acute rheumatic fever and rheumatic heart disease. Nat Rev Dis Primers 2, 15084. 2016. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1038/nrdp.2015.84","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. Robbins Basic Pathology (10th ed.). 2017. Elsevier - Health Sciences Division"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41019"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14452"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41019"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-15T20:26:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T20:27:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7147"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55479"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"d